                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the real concern isn't with DVDs, it's with the new TIVO ability to fast forward through ads shown during television shows.  Every broadcasting station pretty much makes its money by charging major bucks to companies in order to advertise in 10-15-30 second time slots.  If you remove that advertising revenue, the fear is that broadcasting companies will be crippled.  
<br />

<br />
More than that, there is an argument to be made that gadgets like TIVO only make money through the work of the broadcasting companies (i.e., if NBC/etc was not broadcasting shows, TIVO could not sell a machine that helped the user search, organize and record those shows).  And those broadcasting companies require the revenues attached to ads shown during shows.  Selling a machine that capitalizes on the broadcast at the expense of eliminating the ads could arguably be considered unfair competition. 
<br />

<br />
This latter argument, of course, does not effect the ultimate consumer.  I'm not convinced the bill does either, though.  I really think it's targetted at the TIVO-type companies, which design and sell products that explicitly permit the user to easily bypass ads on television.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.therambler.net/images/sigs/vigdissig3.jpg" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370909" target="_blank" class="postlink">Oppressor Vigdis Sang'Carus</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=395059" target="_blank" class="postlink">Mistress Melcindria Ashn'i</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
